><Code value="nfact"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Factiva Filters</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:c314"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="nfcpin"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">C&amp;E Industry News Filter</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:c314"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Opinion</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">The Straits Times says; Weigh new factor in fare formula</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>The latest revision to the public transport fare formula calls for deliberation because it brings into focus the strategic intent of containing the gulf between transport fares and operating costs as the network grows. The means identified is the concept of a Network Capacity Factor (NCF). Commuters would find it difficult to grasp this, compared to other factors like changes to manpower, maintenance and energy costs, which collectively form almost two-thirds of operating costs.</Para><Para>The new factor's rationale is to better reflect cost movements that are caused by changes in the public transport network capacity - for example, the running of more buses and trains over longer distances - and commuter usage, like more passengers taking more trips on buses or trains. "With the NCF, the widening gap between fares and costs due to capacity enhancements can be better contained going forward," said the Public Transport Council, an independent body that regulates public transport fares.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>The opacity of the NCF has led some to view it as a tool for a tax on the use of the network. As one Straits Times reader observed: Commuters "are the same people who contribute annually to building the nation's infrastructure. Why tax them twice?" NCF is in fact a gauge of changes in capacity made available within the network in relation to changes in usage. Opposing scenarios would be when more seats are filled over longer distances as bus and train trips multiply; and conversely, when demand growth is weak compared to the growth in network capacity. The first would represent optimal usage of costly infrastructure; and the second, inefficient usage.</Para><Para>The expansion of the public transport network is obvious. Capacity increased by around 25 per cent from 2012 to 2017, with more than 1,000 new buses introduced and about 200 new trains added. A denser network has also helped commuters to shorten travel times. Such network expansion has resulted in structural changes to operating costs. The annual figure rose by over $900 million between 2012 and 2016; while yearly fare revenue grew by around $230 million, mostly due to greater use of public transport. This revenue works out to about just 25 per cent of the cost increase. The gap was filled by considerable state subsidies, while fares were reduced for the past three consecutive years.</Para><Para>How should one frame a discussion of rising public transport costs being borne by taxpayers? Rather than illuminating the issue, the NCF creates fog with terms like "the change in place kilometres per passenger kilometre over the preceding year". Apportioning costs between the State and users needs more discussion, as public transport fulfils important economic, political and social objectives as well, in keeping people on the move efficiently and affordably.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field"></Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

